{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"de182978-6702-4962-888a-f9a41a2ceaaf","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **implicit span conversions**: `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes **overload resolution** — `array.Contains(num)` now binds to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)   // ← C# 14 picks this (more specific)\n```\n\ninstead of the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)        // ← C# 13 picked this\n```\n\nExpression trees **cannot represent ref structs** like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the expression tree compilation/interpretation fails at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler selects the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:\n\n**Option A** — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly (clearest):\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B** — cast to `IEnumerable<int>` so the span overload is no longer a candidate:\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces the compiler back to the `IEnumerable<T>` extension method, which expression trees can represent. The same pattern applies to other `MemoryExtensions` methods (`IndexOf`, `SequenceEqual`, etc.) that now win overload resolution for arrays in C# 14.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2c20d4d9-f293-4ff8-a1ed-0c513eaff1f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"extension everything\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Array` now implements `IEnumerable<T>` directly (or there's a change in how extension methods are resolved for arrays).\n \nI'm realizing the breaking change probably involves how the compiler prioritizes extension method resolution. In earlier versions, `array.Contains()` would resolve to the LINQ extension method, but .NET 10 might have introduced a new overload or changed the resolution order, potentially affecting how these calls work in expression trees. with that comes changes to member lookup. But more specifically, I think the issue might be:\n\n1. **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** - In recent .NET versions, `MemoryExtensions` has a `Contains` method for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. With .NET 10's implicit span conversions (array to span), the compiler might now prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains`.\n\n2. The expression tree compiler doesn't support `Span<T>` operations because spans are ref structs and can't be used in expression trees.\n\nYes, I think this is the issue. In .NET 10 / C# 14, there's a feature called **implicit span conversions** where `T[]` can implicitly convert to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`.\n\nSo when the compiler encounters `array.Contains(num)`, it's now resolving to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. But expression trees can't handle ref structs or spans at all, so this should fail at compile time, not runtime. Yet the user says it throws at runtime, which makes me reconsider. The expression tree itself might compile fine if it's still referencing the `Enumerable.Contains` method, but something's happening at runtime during interpretation with `preferInterpretation: true` that's causing the issue. In .NET 10, `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` might have been changed, or there might be a new overload. Or perhaps the issue is that the **expression tree interpreter** has a bug or behavioral change.\n\nLet me think again about the implicit span conversions angle. In C# 14 / .NET 10:\n- `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now an implicit conversion\n- The compiler prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` because `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is more specific than `IEnumerable<T>`\n\nBut in an expression tree lambda (`Expression<Func<...>>`), the compiler can't use span-based methods because expression trees don't support ref structs.\n\nSo the expression tree compiles successfully, but when I invoke it with `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` or just call it, it throws at runtime. That suggests the expression tree is being created with something that can't actually execute. Or maybe .NET 10 added a native `Contains` instance method directly to `int[]` through some interface, which would change how overload resolution works. Contains`), and the expression tree compilation/interpretation doesn't handle this correctly.\n\nActually, I think I need to be more precise. Let me reconsider the implicit span conversion angle: The C# 14 compiler, when building an expression tree, encounters `array.Contains(num)`. Due to implicit span conversions, overload resolution selects `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)`. But this involves a ref struct (`ReadOnlySpan<int>`), which cannot be used in expression trees. In previous C# versions, the compiler would have selected `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` because there was no implicit conversion from `int[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<int>`.\n\nSo the compiler either errors at compile time with a ref struct restriction, or still compiles but produces a broken expression tree at runtime. Since the user says it throws at runtime, that suggests the second scenario or something else entirely.\n\nMaybe the compiler still selects `Enumerable.Contains` in the expression tree context due to restrictions, but something changed in .NET 10 that breaks the runtime behavior. Or perhaps the expression tree gets built correctly, but the interpreter has a bug in .NET 10. Let me step back and think about this from the .NET 10 breaking changes angle—there's a known change related to `Enumerable.Contains` optimization for arrays that might be relevant here. The issue is that expression trees can't represent ref struct operations like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so when C# 14's implicit span conversions cause the compiler to resolve `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, it creates an expression tree that references an unsupported method, causing a runtime failure.\n\nSince the user reports a runtime error rather than a compile-time one, the expression tree likely compiles successfully but fails during interpretation at runtime, possibly due to overload resolution changes in C# 14 or differences in how .NET 10's expression tree interpreter handles these methods.\n\nThe most probable cause is that C# 14's implicit span conversions are now making `MemoryExtensions.Contains` on `ReadOnlySpan<T>` a better match than `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays, but expression trees can't represent ref struct operations, causing the runtime failure. The workaround would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the original overload resolution.\n\nThough if this were caught at compile time, the error would be clearer—so the runtime failure suggests the compiler might be resolving to the span-based method without properly detecting the ref struct incompatibility in the expression tree lowering path, which could be a gap in how the new conversion rules interact with expression tree compilation. I'm reconsidering whether the compiler would catch this at compile time or if it only fails at runtime. The C# compiler has specific validation for expression trees and should reject unsupported constructs like ref structs during compilation, so this might actually be a compile-time error rather than a runtime one. I'm wondering if the compiler might be silently falling back to `Enumerable.Contains` when it detects the ref struct issue in an expression tree context, rather than throwing a compile-time error—and that fallback could be what's causing the runtime problem in .NET 10.\n\nLet me just focus on the core issue: C# 14's implicit span conversions are changing the overload resolution for `Contains` on arrays, and that's what I should explain.","outputTokens":3830,"requestId":"6814:278C9F:5EB74E8:672FBD7:69F004FF"},"id":"25826137-f984-4c17-a6e6-07c6659a5945","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:54:35.833Z","parentId":"79ce3731-e3b7-49b2-9ac6-41523f184554"}
